---
id: wai-enter-tool-prompt-v1
title: "wai-enter.sh: prompt for tool name when no arg passed"
version: 1
safe_to_auto_adopt: true
target_files:
  - wai-enter.sh
---

## Problem

`wai-enter.sh` previously defaulted to launching `claude` when called with no argument:

```bash
TOOL="${1:-claude}"
```

This broke the intended workflow for users who want to choose their tool interactively after the prep steps run. It also made it impossible to use `wai-enter.sh` as a general pre-launch wrapper without committing to a specific tool upfront.

## Fix

Prompt interactively when no tool is specified, so `wai-exit.sh` still runs after the session:

```bash
TOOL="${1:-}"
if [[ -n "$TOOL" ]]; then
    shift
fi

if [[ -z "$TOOL" ]]; then
    read -r -p "[wai-enter] Tool to launch (claude/gemini/codex/uvx): " TOOL
fi
```

Also pass remaining `"$@"` args to the tool to support patterns like:
```bash
./wai-enter.sh uvx code-puppy -i
```

## Prerequisites

- `wai-enter.sh` must exist in spoke root
- Must contain the old `TOOL="${1:-claude}"` pattern

## Batch Sequence

1. Replace `TOOL="${1:-claude}"` with the new prompt block above
2. Ensure `"$TOOL" "$@"` is used at launch (not just `"$TOOL"`)
3. Test: `./wai-enter.sh` — should prompt, not auto-launch

## Notes

GUI tools (VS Code, Cursor) still work with this pattern for the prep steps, but `wai-exit.sh` fires immediately after the GUI launcher returns. This is expected — GUI tools are not interactive CLI sessions.
